[3.4 Additional Basic Operations]
    (3.4.1 The Rename Operation)
        - "as" clause
            ex) select something as teacher
            ex) select T.name from instructor as T

            -> useful in renaming relations
            -> reasons
                1. one reason to rename a relation: shortened version which is more convenient to use elsewhere in the query
                2. where we wish to compare tuples in the same relation.

        - "correlation name" in the SQL standard
            -> commonly referred to as a "table alias", or a "correlation variable", or a "tuple variable"

    (3.4.2 String Operations)
        - SQL permits a variety of functions on character strings
            -> concatenating using "∥"
            -> extracting substrings
            -> find the length of strings
            -> converting strings to uppercase(upper(s))
            -> converting strings to lowercase(lower(s))
            -> removing spaces at the end of the string(trim(s))

        - Pattern matching can be performed on strings using "like" operator.
            -> Percent(%): The % character matches any substring
            -> Underscore(_): The _ character matches any character

            ex) Intro%
                -> any string beginning with "Intro"

            ex) %Comp%
                -> any string containing "Comp" as a substring
                    ex) Computer Science, Computational Biology

            ex) ___
                -> matches any string of exactly three characters

            ex) ___%
                -> matches any string of at least three characters

    (3.4.3 Attribute Specification in the Select Clause)
        - "*" symbol: all attributes

    (3.4.4 Ordering the Display of Tuples)
        - "Order by"
            -> lists items in ascending order.

            <-> "desc" for descending

    (3.4.5 Where-Clause Predicates)
        - "between" comparison
            ex) select * from instructor where salary
                between 90 and 100;

        <-> "not between"
